---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/ui/TableOfContents';
import MethodologyCard from '../../components/ui/MethodologyCard.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long do PC power supplies last?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A high-quality PSU with Japanese capacitors typically lasts 7 to 10 years under normal gaming loads. Budget units using cheaper Chinese or Taiwanese capacitors may begin degrading within 3 to 5 years."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does PSU wattage degrade over time?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, capacitor aging causes power supplies to lose efficiency and maximum power output over time (roughly 2% to 5% loss per year after several years of heavy use)."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="PSU Lifespan: Capacitor Aging & Upgrades Guide — PSUCheck"
  description="Learn about the lifespan of PC power supplies, the impact of capacitor aging, warranty policies, and how to identify when your PSU needs an upgrade."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <a href="/methodology" class="badge badge-safe" style="text-decoration:none;">✓ Sizing Methodology Verified</a>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>PSU Lifespan &amp; Capacitor Aging</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Power supplies do not last forever. This guide explains capacitor aging, PSU lifespan indicators,
          and how to evaluate when your unit requires replacement.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>Capacitor Degradation</h2>
          <p>
            The primary failure point in old PSUs is the electrolytic capacitors. These contain liquid electrolytes
            that slowly dry out over time, especially when exposed to high heat (above 40°C ambient).
          </p>
          <p>
            As capacitors age, their Equivalent Series Resistance (ESR) increases, reducing their ability to clean
            up voltage ripple. This manifests as random BSODs, system freezes, or failed cold boots.
          </p>

          <h2>Standard Lifespan Expectancy</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Premium Tier (Corsair RMx, Seasonic Focus):</strong> 10-year warranties. Often last 10-12 years safely.</li>
            <li><strong>Mid-Tier (Bronze/Gold units under $100):</strong> 5-year warranties. Usually reliable for 5-7 years.</li>
            <li><strong>White/Budget Tier:</strong> 2 to 3-year warranties. Recommend replacement after 3-4 years.</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="important-warning">
            <strong>⚠ Upgrade Guideline:</strong> If you are upgrading from an older GPU (like RTX 3070) to a modern
            RTX 50-series card, and your PSU is older than 5 years, do not reuse it. The intense transient peaks
            on Blackwell/RDNA4 architectures will quickly expose degraded capacitors, causing shutdowns.
          </div>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check age derating math</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <TableOfContents client:load />
          <MethodologyCard />
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/how-to-test-a-psu">How to Test a PSU</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-sizing-guide">PSU Sizing Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/single-vs-multi-rail">Single vs Multi Rail</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.important-warning { background: var(--color-surface-raised); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent-orange); padding: 1rem; border-radius: var(--radius-md); margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
